<TEXT>
the american red cross has begun focusing on 
longterm plans to help earthquakestricken soviet armenia rebuild 
its destroyed and damaged health care facilities 
richard f schubert president of the american red cross said 
the pipeline of emergency aid supplies is full and flowing well and 
no further immediate aid is needed at this time 
priority attention is being given to the construction of a new 
general hospital he told a news conference friday the earthquake 
destroyed the only one killing all doctors and staff inside the 
building 
in a related development the office of presidentelect bush said 
his son and grandson are flying to soviet armenia over the christmas 
weekend to deliver toys and medical supplies to earthquake victims 
jeb bush 35 a miami real estate developer and his son george 
12 will spend about six hours in yerevan the armenian capital on 
christmas day 
the bushes are traveling to armenia as volunteers for americares 
a private relief agency that has chartered a dc8 cargo plane to 
transport supplies to the region when 55000 people were killed in 
the earthquake and about 500000 were left homeless 
schubert said the red cross has received 35 million in cash 
contributions and pledges for armenia disaster relief and that more 
money is coming in every hour 
he said the red cross will use the funds to help replace health 
and medical facilities that were destroyed by the dec 7 earthquake 
the red cross will be prepared to help fill any gaps that appear 
at the request of the soviet red cross he said 
schubert said priority longterm needs in armenia include 
the building of a general hospital to replace one that was 
totally destroyed in the quake 
the creation of a facility to make and install artificial limbs 
the establishment of a permanent tracking center to trace 
families of earthquake victims 
a disaster preparedness program to reduce deaths and injuries in 
the event of another earthquake in armenia 
the rebuilding and expansion of a destroyed school for 
handicapped children 
schubert who returned thursday from an inspection tour of the 
disaster areas in armenia said 27000 railroad cars of relief 
supplies have arrived so far in addition to 148 planes carrying 
emergency equipment 
he said soviet officials have been conscientious in keeping track 
of the incoming supplies they have promised to return expensive 
equipment to donors or to seek permission to use it elsewhere once 
it is no longer needed in armenia he said 
there have been reports of confusion and inept rescue efforts at 
the disaster scene but schuster said he believes the work went well 
given the immensity of the destruction and the relative inexperience 
of soviet officials in disaster relief 
given the size of the disaster i think they responded well 
he said its impossible to have a disaster site in which there is 
not confusion initially 
in addition he said it should be noted that in the first day or 
so all of the people present were affected they all lost family 
members 
the people displayed wonderful warmth and dignity schubert 
said time after time they expressed their thanks to the american 
public particularly to thank those in the americanarmenian 
community he said when they stopped to thank us on the streets 
the profusion of gratitude made it difficult to hold back tears 
theirs and ours 
schubert said the soviet red cross helped deal with the crisis 
effectively and offered all forms of cooperation to its american 
counterpart 
bad times bring good people together schubert said 
in addition to the 35 million in cash and pledges schubert 
said the american red cross has received more than 8 million worth 
of medical and other supplies and shipped them to armenia 
these include kidney dialysis machines blood collection bags 
plaster dressings needles and syringes finger splints bandages 
antiseptics sutures cervical collars antibiotics orthopedic 
pins ultrasound machines plastic eating utensils blankets and 
plastic sheeting 
</TEXT>
